03918nam a22006255i 9780271070452DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212015pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710704527 a10.1515/97802710704522doi  a(DE-B1597)584001  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0260002bisacsh04a1942231 aPagani, Karen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMan or Citizen :bAnger, Forgiveness, and Authenticity in Rousseau /cKaren Pagani. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart 1. The Political Significance of Forgiveness and Anger in Rousseau's Thought: The Dialogues as a Case Study -- tPart 2. Private, Interpersonal Forgiveness: The Rousseauvean Intervention -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe French studies scholar Patrick Coleman made the important observation that over the course of the eighteenth century, the social meanings of anger became increasingly democratized. The work of Jean-Jacques Rousseau is an outstanding example of this change. In Man or Citizen, Karen Pagani expands, in original and fascinating ways, the study of anger in Rousseau's autobiographical, literary, and philosophical works. Pagani is especially interested in how and to what degree anger-and various reconciliatory responses to anger, such as forgiveness-functions as a defining aspect of one's identity, both as a private individual and as a public citizen. Rousseau himself was, as Pagani puts it, "unabashed" in his own anger and indignation-toward society on one hand (corrupter of our naturally good and authentic selves) and, on the other, toward certain individuals who had somehow wronged him (his famous philosophical disputes with Voltaire and Diderot, for example). In Rousseau's work, Pagani finds that the extent to which an individual processes, expresses, and eventually resolves or satisfies anger is very much of moral and political concern. She argues that for Rousseau, anger is not only inevitable but also indispensable, and that the incapacity to experience it renders one amoral, while the ability to experience it is a key element of good citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAngerxPhilosophy. 0aForgivenessxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311074525240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271070452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271070452.jpg  a978-3-11-074525-2  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK